The σημεῖον is defined by Aristotle, πρότασις ἀποδεεκτικὴ ἀναγκαία ’ὴ ’ἔνδοξος ; in which the words necessary and probable do not relate to the modal character of the Proposition in itself, but to the nature of its connexion with the Conclusion which it is adduced to prove, i. e. to its loyical validity when the other premise is added⁶; without which addition, eoepressed or understood, there is no Enthymeme at alle.

But it may be thought that the above examples do not furnish a sufficient criterion for distinguishing between the two kinds of Enthymeme. If both premises must be mentally, and may be orally, supplied, before there is any Enthymeme at all, how are we to determine whether any given specimen is an instance of reasoning from a sign, or from a likelihood?
